comments.body:
[~dkavanagh], the root cause is a problem with the OSG.  The problem does have a secondary effect when uploaded from the console, causing the critical worker timeout shown in the description.  I don't have movie software installed on the company computers, however, here is the steps to reproduce and output using the s3cmd utility.
# Configure s3cmd for direct access to OSG
{noformat}
s3cmd --configure
{noformat}
# Modify s3cmd endpoints in {{/root/.s3cfg}}
{noformat}
host_base = objectstorage.cdc-west-1.devlnk.net:8773
host_bucket = %(bucket)s.objectstorage.cdc-west-1.devlnk.net:8773
{noformat}
# Verify size of large file (546M) to be copied
{noformat}
# ls -lh /tmp/large.file
-rwxr-xr-x. 1 root root 546M Aug 31 17:53 /tmp/large.file*
{noformat}
# Upload file to bucket
{noformat}
# s3cmd put /tmp/large.file s3://test
/tmp/large.file -> s3://test/large.file  [1 of 1]
 560492544 of 572096512    97% in   30s    17.33 MB/s  failed
WARNING: Upload failed: /large.file ([Errno 104] Connection reset by peer)
WARNING: Retrying on lower speed (throttle=0.00)
WARNING: Waiting 3 sec...
/tmp/large.file -> s3://test/large.file  [1 of 1]
 559382528 of 572096512    97% in   28s    18.69 MB/s  failed
WARNING: Upload failed: /large.file ([Errno 104] Connection reset by peer)
WARNING: Retrying on lower speed (throttle=0.01)
WARNING: Waiting 6 sec...
{noformat}

The file fails to upload and retries continuously until the operation is cancelled by the user.

[~zhill], No this is not Walrus, it happens on S3-compatible backends.  I made a breakthrough today, I made the following change to increse the queue size from 1 to 2 seconds and I was able to upload large files (1GB was tested) without error:
{noformat}
euca-modify-property -p objectstorage.queue_timeout=2
{noformat}

Oddly enough I discovered this while testing what file size broke, and for some reason when uploading a file right around the breaking point (in our case it was 533MB)
{noformat}
ERROR: S3 error: 400 (400 Bad Request): com.eucalyptus.util.EucalyptusCloudException: Aborting upload, could not process data in time. Either increase the upload queue size or retry the upload later.
{noformat}

This led me to check the ChannelBufferStreamingInputStream.java file and noticed that it is looking for the QUEUE_TIMEOUT variable defined in the Euca Properties.

This, however, does not resolve the issue with the Eucaconsole.  It still appears to have a timeout issue, even though I can directly upload files to the OSG using S3cmd.  This leads me to believe that the Eucaconsole has a separate (possibly similar) timeout variable defined.

I've tracked down the .js code in Eucaconsole to the following in {{bucket_upload.js}}
{code:syntax=python}
$http.post(url, fd, {
                    headers: {'Content-Type': undefined},
                    transformRequest: angular.identity
                  }).
                success(function(oData) {
                    $scope.progress = $scope.progress + 1;
                    if ($scope.progress == $scope.total) {
                        var parentWindow = window.opener;
                        $('#upload-files-modal').foundation('reveal', 'close');
                        $scope.hasChangesToBeSaved = false;
                        parentWindow.postMessage('s3:fileUploaded', '*');
                        $scope.cancel();
                    }
                    if ($scope.uploading == true) {
                        $scope.uploadFile();
                    }
                }).
                error(function(oData, status) {
                    $('#upload-files-modal').foundation('reveal', 'close');
                    $scope.uploading = false;
                    $scope.progress = 0;
                    Notify.failure(oData.message);
                });
        };
{code}

I can't seem to figure out which python code {{$http.post}} triggers, and am having trouble debugging from there.  Any suggestions where to look next?
